===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}

From an earlier form {{zh-l|𥝙}}, attested in the stone drum inscriptions ({{zh-l|石鼓文}}) from the [[w:Warring States period|Warring States period]].

According to {{zh-ref|Chi (2010)}}, the character is an {{Han compound|禾|引|t1=rice plant|t2=to [[draw out]] flowers|ls=ic|nocap=y}} — blooming of a rice plant. The [[w:Shuihudi Qin bamboo texts|Shuihudi Qin bamboo texts]] ({{lw|zh|睡虎地秦簡|睡簡}}) recorded this character as {{lang|zh|⿱禾引}}. The bottom component {{zh-l|弓*}} found in the stone drum inscriptions is likely a reduction of {{zh-l|引*}}.

Xu Kai ({{lw|zh|徐鍇}}), the author of {{lw|zh|pref=《|說文解字繫傳|suf=》}} (10th century AD) gave the following explanation: {{Han compound|禾|乃|ls=p|t1=plant}}, resembling a fruit/an ear hanging off a plant.

[[w:Shuowen Jiezi|''Shuowen'']] states that this character was [[w:naming taboo|tabooed]] at that time (2nd century AD) and so did not elaborate on its origin, due to it being the birth name of [[w:Emperor Guangwu of Han|Emperor Guangwu of Han]].

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} implicitly connects {{cog|tbq-pro|*h(r)u|t=to blow, breathe; life}}, via comparison with {{cog|cdm|स्यु|tr=syu-|t=to prosper, flourish}}. If so, compare {{cog|my|ရှူ|t=to breathe, inhale}}.

Alternatively, perhaps a causative of {{och-l|褎|id=2|growth of seedlings}}. Compare {{cog|mkh-vie-pro|*m-loh||to blossom}} (whence {{cog|vi|trổ||to burst, to open, to display}}, {{m|vi|lổ||naked}}), and {{cog|km|លាស់||to grow, to blossom, to prosper}}. Schuessler prefers the Sino-Tibetan theory above to this theory, however.

